                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.014P/324</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Senator <persName type="from">Joe T. Robinson</persName> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-12-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 31, 1924</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: In making a study of the
                    proposed treaty between the United States and Cuba relating to the Isle of
                        Pines,<note n="1" xml:id="d1fn1">Treaty of Mar. 2, 1904, <ref
                            target="#pg_11">p. 11</ref>.</note> which treaty it appears to me should
                    be ratified, I find that one Senator takes the position that the treaty making
                    power cannot dispose of property belonging to the United States, or divest our
                    Government of sovereignty over any part of its territory.</p>
                <p>I understand that about December, 1904, Secretary Hay addressed a communication
                    to Representative Jenkins, of Wisconsin, bearing upon this phase of the subject,
                    and I would like to be furnished with a copy of this communication for use in
                    preparing to advocate the ratification of the treaty.</p>
                <p>With personal regards [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joe T. Robinson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
